Year = {{2014}},
Number = {{3804}},
Pages = {{1-12}},
Month = {{MAY 22}},
Abstract = {{This, the second study of the nesting biology of Lithurgus chrysurus
   Fonscolombe found at Palmerton, Carbon Co., Pennsylvania, describes its
   nest construction, provisioning, egg deposition, and larval development.
   The first study (Rozen, 2013) was based on observations on the
   late-stage nesting biology in early fall, when these activities were no
   longer being performed. Comparisons are made with activities of the
   native Lithurgopsis apicalis (Cresson); in general, the two species have
   similar, but not identical, nesting biologies. Because Lithurgus
   chrysurus is an adventive bee native to the Mediterranean regions and is
   capable of constructing nests in both soft wood as well as firmer wood,
   it is unclear why it has not expanded its range to any great extent in
